article.description: Sophronia Sallard scored a career-high 20 points and Shayla Scott hit consecutive 3-pointers in overtime to help Pittsburgh beat Rutgers 61-53, ending a 13-game losing streak to its Big East rival.
article.headline: Pitt tops Rutgers in OT for seventh straight win
article.linkText: Pitt ends 13-game losing streak vs. Rutgers
article.story:
PISCATAWAY, N.J. -- The last time Pittsburgh was able to beat Rutgers, most of its current players were in grade school.

Sophronia Sallard scored a career-high 20 points and Shayla Scott hit consecutive 3-pointers in overtime to help Pitt (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 19 AP) top Rutgers 61-53 on Tuesday night, ending a 13-game losing streak to its Big East rival.

"This was a big win for our program," said Pitt coach Agnus Berenato, whose team last beat Rutgers 11 years ago. "We have so much respect for the Rutgers program and its tradition."

Scott finished with 12 points and 12 rebounds and Shavonte Zellous added 15 points for Pitt (18-4, 8-2), which has won seven straight overall. The victory was the Panthers first in 12 tries at the Rutgers Athletic Center.

With the game tied at 49 in overtime, Scott hit a 3-pointer from the top of the key to give Pitt a three-point advantage. Epiphanny Prince made a layup to cut the deficit to one before Scott hit another 3-pointer from the corner with 1:16 left to make it a four-point game.

"I hadn't been shooting well throughout the game, but my teammates told me stay confident," Scott said. "I was really excited. That was the best moments of my life ever."

Prince missed a 3-pointer in the corner and Sallard hit two free throws to seal the victory.

"It means so much to this team," Zellous said. "We haven't beaten Rutgers in a long, long time. Coming in here, we had a good game plan and we executed it and were proud how this team came through in overtime."

Prince scored 21 points for Rutgers (13-9, 5-6), which played its second straight overtime game. The Scarlet Knights beat Georgetown in double overtime on Saturday.

Rutgers held a 41-33 lead with 8:35 left in regulation before Pittsburgh went on a 10-2 run to tie it at 43. Sallard and Scott scored eight of the 10 points during the spurt.

"We had some defensive breakdowns. We didn't make the effort to drop down and see [Sallard]," Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer said.

Kia Vaughn gave Rutgers a 45-43 lead with a turnaround jumper and the Scarlet Knights could've extended the advantage to four, but Brittany Ray missed a layup on the next possession.

Sallard hit a jumper to tie it at 45 on the next possession.

Prince missed a floater in the lane with 35 seconds to go and on the ensuing rebound Nikki Speed threw the ball away, giving Pittsburgh one last chance to win in regulation.

Sallard missed a 15-footer and Scott's follow was blocked out of bounds with 2.3 seconds left.

Zellous caught the ball in the corner off the inbounds, but her jumper bounced off the rim as time expired sending the game to overtime.

Sallard came in averaging six points and her previous career best was 15 points against Wyoming last season.

"Sallard, the last 10 minutes, was tremendous," Berenato said. "For her to come on with 20 points was unbelievable."

Vaughn finished with 11 points and eight rebounds for Rutgers, which played Tuesday night's game in honor of breast cancer awareness and the Kay Yow Cancer Fund. The Scarlet Knights wore pink warmup shirts and shoelaces while the officials used pink whistles. Rutgers plans to wear pink uniforms Sunday when they play at Maryland (No. 9 ESPN/USA Today, No. 11 AP).

Pitt heads up to Connecticut to play the top-ranked Huskies on Sunday.

"I think Connecticut is awesome," Berenato said. "I'm so excited that we have the opportunity to take our ladies up and play the No. 1 team in the country. I think this Connecticut team is one of the best there ever has been."

Zellous, who came in leading the Big East with 24 points a game, was just 5-for-16 shooting. She became the third Pitt women's basketball player to score 2,000 points when she had 29 points in the Panthers' 82-70 victory over Notre Dame on Feb. 3.

Pitt was averaging 79 points before setting a season low against Rutgers. The Panthers struggled to get points against the Scarlet Knights, settling for jumpers.

The Panthers, who averaged 21 free-throw attempts a game, didn't take their first until Zellous was fouled on the fast break nearly two minutes into overtime.

Her free throws gave Pitt a 49-48 advantage before Rashidat Junaid tied it making 1-of-2 foul shots.
